Articles.Content:
4 minutes ago, JoelleEmmily said:

@LatiMacciato I didn't have it installed before, so I installed it. I really don't like the decoration/resize/etc tweaks. Will these workarounds work without those enabled?

i believe so, theyre telling compiz (composite/OpenGL libs) to act this way you set, you should play around with that and see what effect they have .. option for option ..and if you dont notice any change relog/restart into your OS to apply

i had set my shadows and window decoration to somewhat different too before on my 32bit Ubuntu 14.04 (wich is now on 16.04 aswell) but came to the clue to leave the standard theme as it is and taking care of customization later once i have time and nerves for it .. including window deco's and shadows

Edited August 25, 2016 by LatiMacciato

@LatiMacciato Nope, you can't. If you don't load those plugins, you lose your window and control bars. Sad me. But, I guess I now know there's something wrong with the vid driver.

Edited August 25, 2016 by JoelleEmmily
spell check

1 hour ago, JoelleEmmily said:

@LatiMacciato Nope, you can. If you don't load those plugins, you lose you window and control bars. Sad me. But, I guess I know know there's something wrong with the vid driver
.

May I ask you to provide the text output of:
$ glxinfo
under the spoiler? The large extensions table (slow, none etc) can be skipped. I wonder what driver, what card and what profile are you using.

The issues in the vid are issues between Window manager and Driver in regard to correct transfer of "damaged" (by window move) screen areas.

Thank you.

Edited August 25, 2016 by Kerbal101

Actually - no.
The classic fglrx (FireGL dRiver for X11) is non existent "old old" proprietary driver now. The "new old" (with "new new" being AMDGPU+ << note the plus) Catalyst is the all-proprietary much more generic driver sourced mostly from Windows driver (as opposed to dedicated workstation-oriented fglrx development), that replaced fglrx but still goes by same name internally.

The classic fglrx is a very old, crash-prone, proprietary-only (present both as kernel module and userspace) driver that worked reliably only with specific cards, on specific distros (mostly SUSE and Redhat) and specific applications.
It could crash even when you loaded basic GNOME 2 desktop.


Even then, don't underestimate the capability of open driver (which OP is using; here performance for hd6950 from 2015 between the two), as its this driver that runs all recent AMD GPUs by default.
Since around 2014, the open driver is the default driver for all AMD cards in Linux. Installing Catalyst or AMDGPU+ is only viable is there are serious issues with newer hardware or more fps is desired. Bugreports for the kernel and desktop will probably be ignored, because they taint kernel.


The mentioned AMDGPU (without plus) is also an open driver. As an option, modern proprietary driver AMDGPU+ can be installed, that basically is an extension on top of the open driver and replaces only libraries.

 

The CAYMAN indicate a HD69xx GPU, which is the HD6950 the OP previously mentioned. The driver is r600g, same as the one I am using.

This driver runs KSP 1.1.3 perfectly - if you don't count the famous missing text bug (see this bug), which is worked around with " -force-glcore33" for me.

It also run KSP 1.0.5 perfectly without single issue.

I am sure that the issues, which JoelleEmmily experiences, are caused by driver instability in combination which he is using.

I suggest the following:

1. remove and uninstall oibaf or similar Mesa replacements, fallback to opendriver shipped by your distribution. If the issues disappear, see the latest step
2. if you want to persue recent opendriver developments, make sure you are using latest possible Linux kernel! For example, I use Mesa 11.1.3 with Linux Kernel 4.6.4 and encounter no issues.
3. do use proprietary driver, if nothing helped to test if this caused by driver or other software stack (such as your WM). Be warned though, that Catalyst and AMDGPU+ might introduce own issues - and these drivers will eventually drop support for your card. Open driver will not, thus its in your own interest to push bug evidence to the devs (see below).
4. search and fire a bug at radeon bugtracker, shipping all the evidence. If the bug is only specific to hardware, it will be ressolved by the developers and you will  be possibly given workarounds.
 

Edit: what also bothers me, is if you have the DRI3 enabled. Please try disabling it by setting

LIBGL_DRI3_DISABLE=1

in /etc/environment, rebooting and checking with

echo $LIBGL_DRI3_DISABLE

in the terminal.

6 hours ago, JoelleEmmily said:

AMDGPU-Pro doesn't function on this card, and I have yet to try AMDGPU or AMDGPU+.

Edit: Correction, I think on the HD4830, oibaf made everything screwy,

AMDGPU = new open driver stack, which consist of new open amdgpu kernel driver combined with 3d driver userspace driver part (r100g, r300g, r600g, radeonsi 3d drivers + mesa, llvm)
"AMDGPU-Pro" = "AMDGPU+" =  new proprietary driver stack, which consists of same new open amdgpu kernel driver, but the 3d driver in userspace is replaced with proprietary chunks.

Sure, drivers built on new method (AMDGPU/AMDGPU+) do not work with anything below Southern Islands (HD7xxx) and above because HD7xxx...HD3xxx GPUs are quite different (VLIW-based). All previous GPUs are to be supported by existing open driver - radeon kernel driver family (r100g, r300g, r600g, radeonsi), which is why its in best owner interest to submit a bug if anything breaks on this driver.

Radeon = open radeon kernel driver with 3d driver userspace driver part (r100g, r300g, r600g, radeonsi 3d drivers + mesa, llvm)
Catalyst = will be depricated, means new versions to support new Linux kernels will stop supporting it. Kinda same like Nvidia legacy proprietary driver.

Its not oibaf directly, its so called "regressions", the price for the cutting edge. You may encounter same regressions with any proprietary beta driver.
I am basically using same driver - but last stable release, and my GPU is very close to yours (VLIW5, yours is more "optimized" VLIW4), and I encounter no such issues.
 

This is why I strongly suggest you to report the bug, if you find out that its the open driver, who is causing it! You can then perhaps get developers issue a patch, which will very soon make into current open driver - and in oibaf! In the long run, this means your HD6950 card will have this issue corrected. If nobody reports bugs, then when Catalyst is depricated, your GPU may be left in buggy state forever.

Why I am sure of 3d driver causing issues is because open driver consists of two separate pieces: kernel driver radeon and 3d driver (r600g in your case), its quite capable to crash a 3d application or even desktop (although only part doing compositing(3d thing): window manager (kwin, metacity, compiz etc) - so you will experience several flicks as it restarts, no huge back-to-login-screen crashes).
In case of old fglrx, it could easily crash whole machine, because kernel modesetting was not existent and the blob that attached everywhere.
The issue you have around window border is clearly a compositing issue of window manager, which can easily be connected with 3d driver incorrectly repainting the texture.

 

Regarding the Catalyst or AMDGPU+ "fps galore" I should warn you, because Catalyst is known to give more fps - but the fps output is way less fluid. Its great if you don't encounter this; and since migration to new proprietary sandwich, AMDGPU+ started to underperform - being close to AMDGPU.
Most of Linux AMD users want single open driver which their entire Linux team should work upon, but AMD still thinks that those tiny "optimizations" for its FireGL segment cards have to remain proprietary. Still a major step in right direction.

So I'm not really in on the discussion but like to add my two cent experience:

I have teh Radeon R7 260X (southern islands) reasonably modern card. I've always used the open-source radeon with it, and due to talks I decided to try out amdgpu with it.

My card specifically is still not officially supported by amdgpu, so I did need a custom compiled kernel with the necessary option enabled. That was only to enable the x11 driver and kernel module, I came with plenty of issues when doing this back and forth, seems that the amdgpu package comes with a file that basically forces x11 so use its module, blocking you of radeon.

So after you enable the kernel to use it with my card, its finally able to run the amdgpu module, but still uses the open-source driver stack radeonsi. Now what I needed was the proprietary blob caleld amdgpu-pro, luckily was easy enough for me, got everything from the AUR.

After all that finally confirmed to be running the amdgpu kernel module and the amdgpu+ driver stack.

After some quick testing I came to the conclusion the the new amdgpu+ was incredible lower in performance than what it was before, noticeable on some games, even glxinfo reported pretty lower fps. So there was actually a good reason to not fully support my card yet.

So what I'm trying to say is: the new driver may not be the best for you, seems to be mainly aimed at R9 cards at that new model they launched recently.  Also that there may be some confusion regarding the module amdgpu and driver amdgpu+. To make sure what is going on, always read on the Xorg log.

the vblank_mode=0 really disables vsync, which improves performance. According to glxosd, I get 70 fps on KSCenter overview screen, where with vsync enabled - only 40-47.
setting this to 1 or not exporting, causes vsync to be always enabled regardless of settings. Glxosd reports 16-60 fps regardless of where.
